<p>Unlike the double pendulum, this is very easy to isolate explicitly for the acceleration terms (Iâ€™ll spare the details, itâ€™s easy enough though)</p>

<h2 id="numerical-solutions">Numerical solutions</h2>

<p>So I used a built-in scipy solver (solve_ivp) for my first tests, it also represents the â€œtrueâ€ solution (Iâ€™m placing more confidence in Pythonâ€™s estimation. Some method called â€œRadauâ€ of which I have no knowledge). But then to actually use the knowledge of the class, I converted some of my matlab (ğŸ¤®) functions to python (ğŸ˜). I have:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Eulerâ€™s method</li>
  <li>Runga Kutta 2</li>
  <li>Runga Kutta 3</li>
  <li>Runga Kutta 4</li>
</ul>

<p>Runga-Kutta 2 is pretty good as is; when I overlayed solutions with 3 and 4, I could hardly see a difference. Particularly when the masses came to a stop. Eulerâ€™s method sucks though (he was a brilliant dude for sure, but for his method to give nice results, the step size has to be tiny which isnâ€™t amenable to fast calculation).</p>

<h2 id="animation">Animation</h2>

<p>I initially animated the solutions with Matplotlibâ€™s animation class. But when it ran, my computer fan would kick up. I also wasnâ€™t able to get it to continuously run, I could only calculate the entire trajectory ahead of time, then run it.</p>

<p>In order to make the animation run continuously, I used Pygame and put a condition to recalculate the trajectory after reaching the end of the one currently being plotted. It was a natural part of the loop. It required finding a sweet spot where I donâ€™t calculate too many terms (for fear of seeing a visible pause) and I donâ€™t calculate too few terms in each loop (to avoid slowing down from needing to use pythonâ€™s C API too frequently).</p>

<p><img src="/blog/assets/dynamic_systems/matplotlib_animation.gif" alt="matplotlib animation" /></p>

<p>The Pygame gif below isnâ€™t as smooth. My screencapture working at the same time led to jerky rendering. But it actually looks smoother and is definitely faster when run locally. The Matplotlib animation above was sped up to 3x speed.</p>

<p><img src="/blog/assets/dynamic_systems/pygame_animation.gif" alt="pygame animation" /></p>

